<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Consumer credit 'shows fall but 31% up on year'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumers took out 8 per cent less credit in April than in March, according
to figures released by the Finance and Leasing Association today.
The figures are not seasonally adjusted, however, and may reflect the
restricted number of trading days in April because of the Easter holidays.
Compared with April 1993 consumer credit showed a 31 per cent increase at
Pounds 1.34bn, the association said.
Economists have been watching for evidence that consumer behaviour has been
affected by the impact of April's tax increases on pay packets.
The seasonal effects on the association's figures makes it difficult to draw
firm conclusions. Official figures for April's consumer credit are published
today.
There was further evidence of a diverging trend between credit on store
cards and credit for larger items such as personal loans or car finance.
Store-card credit fell just 3 per cent between March and April and was still
46 per cent higher than a year ago. Both personal loans and motor finance
saw a 12 per cent fall between March and April, and are respectively only 19
per cent and 25 per cent higher than a year ago.
Business finance showed a fall in the rate of growth, with April's leasing
total 17 per cent lower than a year ago. Hire purchase was up 25 per cent
year-on-year.
Mr David Hardisty, chairman of the FLA, said: 'Although there are
indications of an economic upturn, there seems to be a wait and see attitude
among businesses. They still need to be convinced that the recovery will
last before making investment commitments.'
Figures from Infolink, the credit information group, show that credit
applications in the retail sector in April were 10.7 per cent higher than in
April last year.
The annual rate of increase for home-loan applications, and for new-car
loans, fell between March and April.
</TEXT>
