<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Industry image set for another battering: Employers and
ex-sales agents are preparing for battles in the courtroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The arcane phrase 'commission clawback' will soon start reverberating
through the courts as part of an extraordinary battle between some of
Britain's biggest insurers and hundreds of their former sales agents.
At stake are several tens of millions of pounds in lost earnings and fees
which an estimated 400 to 1,000 agents claim they are owed by their former
companies. In many of these cases the agents have themselves been issued
with writs from their former companies, arguing that they should repay large
sums of commission paid on insurance policies that have lapsed.
The courtroom recriminations - assuming enough cases reach trial rather than
being settled privately - are likely further to harm the image of the
insurance industry.
By concentrating on the often complex and contentious relationship between
companies and their sales staffs, the court cases will shed more light on
the patchy nature of the controls over sales agents which has been a factor
behind recent allegations of mis-selling of life products such as pensions.
They may also lead, however unlikely this appears, to a surge of public
sympathy for life insurance agents - who are generally portrayed as sharks
attempting to extort money out of unsuspecting consumers.
Mr Tony Whiteley of the MSF general technical union said: 'A lot of these
people are not villains but victims.' The union is co-ordinating legal help
for several hundred former agents.
In the late 1980s the life industry expanded enormously, taking on tens of
thousands of sales agents to sell products such as life insurance and
private pensions to cash-rich consumers.
However, the recession and tougher regulations introduced by the industry's
regulator Lautro, which have raised the quality threshold for sales staff,
have encouraged insurers to shed agents. The number of registered agents has
shrunk by half since 1990 to about 100,000.
Many of the agents who have lost their jobs, most of whom were
self-employed, had their contracts terminated.
Partly because of the complexity of these contracts and the way insurance
companies stage commission payments to sales representatives over a long
period, the parting has often been acrimonious.
A crucial area of dispute concerns the repayment of loans, often amounting
to tens of thousands of pounds, which many companies handed to sales people
 -particularly 'tied agents' working at arms-length - during the 1980s
expansion.
Even more contentious have been altercations over commission clawback -
efforts by insurance companies to reclaim commission paid to sales agents on
life products that lapsed after the client stopped paying premiums.
An insidious part of the clawback practice - as far as many former sales
people are concerned - is that under Lautro rules once they have run up a
debt of more than Pounds 1,000 on clawback they are not allowed to work for
other insurance companies. In some cases this has severely limited their
chances of finding alternative employment.
Take Mr Vojislav (Joe) Sujdovic, who sold insurance and pensions for
Guardian Royal Exchange between 1988 and 1990. According to Mr Sujdovic GRE
is claiming Pounds 53,000 from him on the basis of 'clawback'. He says that
because of the debt he has been unable to get another insurance job. He now
works as a Pounds 100-a-week garage attendant, earning a tenth of what he
made at GRE.
In Mr Sujdovic's case - which has yet to come to court and which GRE did not
want to comment on - he has countered the clawback claim with a writ
alleging that GRE owes him Pounds 69,000 on unpaid commission and lost
earnings.
The sums of money involved in this case are dwarfed by some of the amounts
in other disputes.
Mr Chris Price, a former Legal &amp; General agent, is pursuing his former
company for about Pounds 100,000 in loss of income and commission payments.
Mr Joseph Meade, a former Pounds 75,000-a-year Colonial Mutual salesman who
is now seeking work in Thailand, has a claim for damages and wrongful
termination of contract against his company for Pounds 500,000.
In both these cases the companies involved also have claims against the two
men - of about Pounds 10,000 and Pounds 91,000 respectively.
While Legal &amp; General said it pursued legal action only after thinking 'long
and hard' and did not want to discuss individual cases, Colonial Mutual said
there had been a 'breakdown in the relationship' with Mr Meade. It felt it
was pursuing the matter fairly.
Probably the biggest claim is that being made through a writ by Mr Hugh
Beaumont, a former GRE agent who reckons the company owes him Pounds 2.5m
due to loss of earnings and commission. In this case GRE has a counter-claim
calling for repayment of Pounds 119,000 on a repayable development grant and
commission.
Assuming the case gets to a High Court trial - which is unlikely before the
middle of next year at the earliest - critics and supporters of the
insurance industry alike will be packing the aisles. The public image of the
industry will be in for another battering.
</TEXT>
