<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / City prosperity boosts pay in finance sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Managerial pay increases in the finance sector averaged 3.7 per cent in the
first quarter compared with 2.9 per cent in the final three months of last
year, says the latest survey of managerial pay published today by Incomes
Data Services, the independent research body.
The return of economic prosperity in the City of London was one of the
factors explaining the upturn, IDS said.
Of the top five managerial pay awards in the first quarter of the year in
the sector, three were paid by City institutions. However, increases were
mainly based on merit and performance payments.
'The basic salary budget increases for these employers ranged from 5.9 per
cent to 7 per cent,' the report said. It added: 'Because these pay-bill
figures include support staff, they tend to understate the actual salary
rises paid to 'front office' professionals such as dealers.'
IDS added that the high City pay rises were 'not simply driven by an upturn
in economic activity' but also reflected 'the re-emergence of recruitment
and retention problems'.
Overall, private-sector managerial pay awards averaged 3.1 per cent over the
first quarter. Manufacturing averaged 2.8 per cent.
In a separate report on overall pay trends, IDS says there is a 'gentle
upswing' in the level of pay settlements with nearly half the 129 wage
settlements reported to it in April running at 3 per cent and above. But the
survey suggests there are 'few signs of an inflationary spiral developing'.
However, Industrial Relations Services, another independent research
organisation, suggests there has been 'no further pick-up in the level of
pay settlements since annual pay awards moved upward' at the start of 1994.
In its latest pay survey, IRS suggests basic wage increases in the private
sector were 'holding steady at 2.5 per cent' in the three months to the end
of April.
Management Pay Review 160. IDS Report 666. Incomes Data Services, 193 St
John Street, London ECIV 4LS.
IRS Pay and Benefits Bulletin 353. Industrial Relations Services, 18-20
Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
</TEXT>
