<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUN 94 / Delors faces fight for 'Union bonds'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, faces a test of
strength with the UK and Germany today over his plan to launch 'Union bonds'
to finance trans-European networks, the multi-billion dollar rail, road, and
telecoms infrastructure projects.
Amid strong scepticism in Bonn and London, EU finance ministers will
consider revised proposals for the European Commission to borrow on the
capital markets to help fund the networks, which Mr Delors argues are vital
for improving competitiveness and creating jobs.
Ministers meeting in Luxembourg will also discuss how to improve labour
market flexibility and tackle unemployment, now nearing 18m. A row would
damage prospects for the European summit in Corfu on June 24, which is
already threatened with a showdown over who should succeed Mr Delors as head
of the Commission.
Some diplomats in Brussels are predicting a stormy session today between Mr
Delors and the finance ministers, notably Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK
Chancellor of the Exchequer.
Last month, Mr Delors railed against a German plan to set up an independent
panel of experts to examine whether Brussels legislation is damaging efforts
to improve European competitiveness. Mr Clarke, anxious to build bridges
with Bonn, strongly supported the German deregulation plan, which has won
lukewarm backing from France.
However, Mr Delors is under pressure not to provoke a second confrontation
with the finance ministers. With short-term interest rates falling, German
monetary policy slackening and recovery clearly under way, senior Brussels
officials argue that the prospects for a successful summit are the best in
two years.
Aides to Mr Delors suggested that he might decide to shelve his financing
plan for the trans-European networks until the Essen summit in December, his
last appearance as Commission president.
But he remains convinced that the private sector and the European Investment
Bank alone cannot finance the multi-billion dollar projects - hence the
Commission's plan last week for financing a Ecu5bn (Pounds 3.85bn) alleged
funding gap for 10 infrastructure projects.
'The Commission's paper has reawakened some spectres we though had been
already killed off,' a UK official said.
Another diplomat added: 'We remain extremely sceptical, as do the Germans
among others, about the need for this. At the moment we are not persuaded
that there is a funding gap.'
</TEXT>
