<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / International Company News: Holders defeat Kmart's stock
plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kmart, the troubled US discount store group, yesterday suffered a
humiliating defeat at the hands of its shareholders when dissident
institutional investors succeeded in throwing out the company's
reorganisation plan.
Kmart said although the proposal won the support of 61 per cent of the
shares voted at its annual meeting in Troy, Michigan, the number of
non-voters left the company without the required approval of 50 per cent of
the eligible votes.
Mr Joseph Antonini, chairman and chief executive said he was 'disappointed'
at the outcome. Management and the board would now assess the alternatives
available.
Kmart's plan had been to create new shares in its four specialty retailing
subsidiaries - Builders Square, Borders-Walden, OfficeMax and Sports
Authority - and raise money by selling stakes of up to 30 per cent in each
of them. It intended to retain majority control.
However, six of the company's most powerful institutional investors -
including the College Retirement Equities Fund, Wall Street's biggest
investor - publicly opposed the plan, saying Kmart should sell the
subsidiaries altogether and concentrate on improving the performance of its
ailing discount stores instead.
Some of the dissident investors said they would also withhold support for
the re-election of five board directors to mark their dissatisfaction with
the company's performance, but the five were re-elected yesterday.
The institutions are challenging Kmart's board and management because the
company has been struggling unsuccessfully to compete with its more
successful rival, WalMart.
Last year it ended five years of stagnant earnings by plunging into net
losses of Dollars 947bn.
</TEXT>
