<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / FT Guide to Investment Trusts (14): Nice convertible, pity
about the gearing - Gillian O'Connor test-drives Trustspeak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Annuity share: Useful jargon term for one variety of income share in
split-capital trusts. They get a very high income until the trust is wound
up, but then have only a token claim on the capital. They are a good way of
turning capital into income. But note that the income is taxable unless
shielded in a Pep. The problem for the outsider is that share price pages
and research material do not distinguish them from other income shares with
worthwhile claims on the capital. The give-away is normally the very high
running yield. Estimated redemption yields, though fallible, are probably a
fairer yardstick.
Convertible: Convertible loan stocks are one common form of prior charge
capital and work like any other convertible - ie, stockholders have the
option to convert the stock into shares on fixed terms at fixed times (the
conversion terms). They provide a higher income than the underlying shares
but will produce lower capital growth.
Discount: Conventional way of expressing the difference between the stock
market price of an investment trust share and its net asset value (qv), when
the share is below its asset value. For example, if the asset value is 100p
and the share price 90p, the discount is 10 per cent. When the price is
above asset value, it is said to be at a premium.
Gearing: A capital structure in which certain classes of security have prior
but fixed or limited claims on either or both the income and the capital of
the trust. The presence of these securities normally exaggerates the effect
of changes in income or asset value on securities with secondary but
unlimited claims. Thus, if the trust's income is increasing, the existence
of a fixed-interest loan stock will mean that the income attributable to
shareholders rises faster than the underling income. Similarly, if the
trust's assets are increasing in value, the existence of a stock with fixed
capital claims will mean that the assets attributable to shareholders rises
disproportionately. But in bad times gearing means that both income and
assets attributable to shareholders can shrink faster than the decline in
underlying income and assets. Think of negative equity in houses. Nowadays
gearing in many trusts, particularly split-capital ones, is exceedingly
complex, with several layers of gearing. When a security is said to be
'highly geared', it means it will react very sharply to minor changes in the
underlying portfolio. The high risk/reward ratio makes highly geared shares
unsuitable for novices, widow, orphans, or the bulk of anyone's portfolio.
Gross redemption yield: The average annual yield on a gilt-edged stock,
including both the annual dividend payments and the capital gain/loss
implied by the gap between the current price and the price at which the
stock will eventually be repaid. Stockbrokers' analysts have attempted to
apply a similar system to certain types of investment trust share. This is
plausible with securities such as zero-dividend preference shares (qv) which
have a fixed redemption price, provided there is a realistic prospect of
assets sufficing to cover that redemption price when the trust is wound up.
More contentious are attempts to apply the concept to securities with an
uncertain redemption value, by making various assumptions about portfolio
growth.
Hurdle rate (also known as fulcrum): Warning: meaning varies slightly with
the context. The minimum annual rate at which assets must grow before
certain returns can be achieved. For example, a hurdle rate of 2 means that
assets must grow at 2 per cent a year before assets will cover the current
share price of a particular class of shares, or alternatively - when
relevant - the set future redemption value of a particular class of shares.
A hurdle rate of minus-2 means that assets can decline by 2 per cent a year
before capital backing will not suffice to cover the current share price of
a highly geared ordinary share. But in a different context, it would mean
that assets can decline by 2 per cent a year before assets will not suffice
to cover the future redemption price of a zero-dividend preference share
(qv). Note, then, that a hurdle rate is specific to a particular class of
shares, not to the investment trust as a whole.
Net asset value (NAV): What each ordinary share in a conventional trust
would theoretically be entitled to if the trust were wound up today and the
assets distributed to shareholders; normally expressed in pence per share.
NAV total return is a way of measuring the performance of the trust,
assuming income is reinvested.
Ordinary income share: Anything but. Shares with two different
characteristics. They are usually entitled to all the income from the trust,
but have no claim on the capital until at least one other class of capital,
usually ZDPs (qv) has been fully satisfied. As they get near to winding-up
date, they should behave more like a very highly geared capital share.
Portfolio yield: Average annual income that the managers are getting from
the shares in the investment portfolio. Very broadly, the higher the
portfolio yield, the lower the prospects of capital growth in the portfolio,
and vice versa.
Split-capital trusts: Trusts with several different types of security with
differing rights, and aimed to satisfy different investment needs. Some
commentators refer to split-capital trusts which combine zero-dividend
preference shares (qv) with ordinary income shares (qv) as hybrids.
Subscription price: (Sometimes called exercise price): Price at which a
warrant entitles the holder to buy a certain type of share in a trust.
Redemption price: Price at which the holder of a security has the right to
be repaid at the stated redemption date, provided the trust has sufficient
assets. The security will often have a tapered redemption price in case some
unexpected event, such as a bid, occurs.
Warrant: Traded security, usually issued free to buyers of the ordinary
shares at the original issue, often in the ratio of 1:5. It entitles the
holder to subscribe to a certain type of share in the trust at a fixed price
at fixed dates or over a fixed period.
Winding-up date: Many trusts, and all split-capital trusts, have a limited
life, and shareholders are due to be repaid at a specific date. Occasionally
trusts have extended their life, but this is expensive; the cost is borne by
shareholders, and the extension may not be equally in the interest of all
classes of shareholder.
Zero-dividend preference share (ZDPs): Share in a split-capital trust issued
at substantial discount to its eventual redemption value, but not entitled
to any income in the intervening period. Assets of the trust will normally
suffice to cover the ZDPs when the trust is launched. But if the market
falls thereafter, the value of the ZDPs is endangered. The extent to which
assets cover the promised redemption value is a key statistic.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
