<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / FT Guide to Investment Trusts (9): Venerable institutions to
tempt the cautious - They are virtually unrestricted, explains Bethan
Hutton, yet have a solid UK base
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many people steer clear of the stock market, or anything linked to it,
because of a vague feeling that companies go bust, stock markets crash, and
the world of stocks and shares is populated by fly-by-night outfits which
take your money and run.
Perhaps even the most truly cautious might stick a toe in the water if it
were possible to entrust their money to institutions which had been managing
money since before their grandparents were born, and had survived every
stock market crash this century.
Such institutions do exist: a good number are to be found among the 20 or so
trusts in the international general investment trust sector. Half of them
were launched before 1900, and only four are post-war - the first world war,
that is.
Like the giant, long-lived tortoises on the Galapagos Islands who met Darwin
when he first passed by, and are still munching placidly away a century and
a half later as hordes of eco-tourists follow in his wake, they have seen it
all before.
When the Foreign &amp; Colonial Investment Trust, the most venerable and most
gigantic of them all, came into existence more than 125 years ago, the
emerging markets of the Far East and Latin America were all the rage. Since
then investment fashions have gone through many phases before returning full
circle to the 'newly emerging' markets of the Far East and Latin America.
But these trusts are not lumbering creatures still living in the last
century. Their advantage is their flexibility. You want emerging markets?
The international generalists have got them. You want European
privatisations? UK small-cap stocks? Latin American telephone companies?
Japanese game manufacturers and Australian mines? Foreign &amp; Colonial,
Alliance, Bankers Trust, Mid Wynd, Scottish Mortgage and their like will
probably have them all - if they are worth having, that is, not just this
month's gimmick to launch a new trust.
International general trusts are virtually unrestricted in their investment
policies. They all have a solid base portfolio of UK shares, but can move
funds anywhere in the world if they see markets turning nasty in one corner
of the globe while investment opportunities open up elsewhere. They can
invest in the largest blue-chip stocks or the tiniest start-up venture, as
they see fit.
The one thing they do not all have is fully Pep-qualifying status. Some,
like Scottish Mortgage, have decided to go for Pepability, and so make sure
that their funds are always at least 50 per cent invested in the UK and
Europe.
But others, notably Foreign &amp; Colonial, treasure their complete investment
freedom so that although at times their portfolio may be less than 50 per
cent invested outside the EU, they make no promises that it will remain that
way. Therefore investors can only put up to Pounds 1,500-worth of these
trusts' shares into a Pep each year.
However, most of the management groups run other fully Pepable funds which
can use up the rest of your Pep allowance if you prefer to keep your Pep
under one roof.
Because these trusts spread their assets so widely around different markets,
they are never caught up in the kind of wave of enthusiasm which can pluck
more narrowly-focused trusts from obscurity (and a hefty discount) and make
them flavour of the month (pushing them to a premium), only to drop them
when the next fad comes along. General trusts tend to roll steadily along at
an average sort of discount, neither in nor out of favour.
Investors in highly-specialised trusts can find that when their speciality
falls out of favour, they are hit by a double blow as the share price
plummets and the discount widens to as much as 20 or 30 per cent. But it
would take a collapse in all world markets - not impossible, but not a
frequent occurrence - to deal a heavy blow to the international generalists.
International general trusts provide the ideal basis for the first-time
equity investor's portfolio. They give you a little bit of everything,
without too much exposure to some of the heart-stoppingly volatile
individual markets.
This may mean that you never triple your money in six weeks, in the way your
broker swears you could have done if you had shovelled it all into emerging
market warrants and Latin American debt at the right moment. But you will
also be spared the experience of seeing your money disappear into a black
hole as you try to sell last month's hot tip at the same time as everybody
else.
Independent adviser David Harris, of Chantrey Financial Services, says the
Foreign &amp; Colonial trust is a long-standing favourite of his. 'I think of it
very much in the light that it will never reach extremes and be at the top
of the performance tables, but it is solid, and it has downside protection.'
Another handy feature for cautious or small investors is that most
international generalists have savings schemes which allow you to invest
small, regular amounts, sometimes as little as Pounds 25 a month, to build
up a holding in the fund. This also means you can ride out the ups and downs
of the stockmarket, and avoid investing lump sums at the peak of the market
(see above).
Foreign &amp; Colonial was the first to offer a savings scheme, 10 years ago,
and it continues to evolve: now you can even take out a Foreign &amp; Colonial
personal pension plan. If proof were needed, that gives a clear signal that
these trusts expect to be around for a long time yet.
</TEXT>
