<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / FT Guide to Investment Trusts (7): Your savings in their
hands - Bethan Hutton stages an identity parade for famous names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Do you know who is looking after your money? By buying shares in an
investment trust, you are in effect handing over your savings to the
managers of a trust, hoping they will invest wisely on your behalf. But many
investors have a very hazy idea of who the real people are behind the name
on the share certificate.
It is not always obvious from the name of a trust what it is and who
actually manages it. The Bankers trust is an international generalist run by
Henderson Touche Remnant, as are both Law Debenture and Witan - but who
could have guessed?
Some management groups, like Edinburgh Fund Managers, are gradually changing
the names of their funds to present a unified 'brand image' and increase
awareness of the group behind the funds; but others are reluctant to
sacrifice names which can be a century or more old, and often pre-date the
management company.
Investment trust management is a small but diverse segment of the fund
management industry. The biggest three investment trust management groups
are Henderson Touche Remnant, with Pounds 3,680m under management, Fleming
with Pounds 3,659m, and Foreign &amp; Colonial with Pounds 3,455m. At the
opposite end of the scale, there are also a dozen or two groups with less
than Pounds 50m of investment trust money under management, though for many
of them investment trusts are a sideline to their main insurance, pension
fund or unit trust business.
The large players, like HTR and Fleming, tend to have broad ranges of funds,
with general UK and international funds at their core, supplemented by
portfolios of small specialist trusts.
Smaller groups often concentrate their resources on a particular segment of
the market, such as smaller companies, or the Far East. Niche players are
often the result of one experienced manager or small team breaking away from
well-known houses to follow their own ideas. One example is Scottish Value
Management, set up by former Templeton and Scottish Provident manager Colin
McLean in 1990, which specialises in investing in other investment trusts,
and seeking hidden value in other companies.
As might be expected, many investment trust groups have solid roots in the
City of London. But it is a matter for dispute whether the Scots or the
English invented investment trusts, and the predominance of Scottish accents
is still noticeable in the industry in modern times. Perhaps a third of
investment trust assets are managed north of the border, by groups like
Abtrust, Baillie Gifford, Dunedin, Edinburgh Fund Managers, Ivory &amp; Sime,
Martin Currie, Murray Johnstone, and Templeton - but even the London-based
groups recruit plenty of managers from Scotland.
Charlotte Square, the Georgian square at the heart of Edinburgh's business
and financial district, used to be the hub of the investment trust world, as
it housed many of the large Scottish fund management groups. People used to
talk of the investment community as the 'Charlotte Square mafia', but that
has now been largely disbanded. Many of the companies have moved out to
shiny new headquarters elsewhere in Edinburgh, while others are based in
less traditional Scottish financial centres like Glasgow and Aberdeen. Ivory
&amp; Sime is one of the few old stalwarts remaining, at One Charlotte Square.
In the US, some fund managers are high-profile personalities who can draw
investors to a fund with their name alone. UK investment trusts are
anonymous by comparison, with few names or faces recognisable by the general
investing public. Most funds are run by teams, often composed of one
experienced manager backed up by a number of bright young things trying to
make their mark. However, a few personalities do stand out, particularly at
the more exotic end of the market.
One such is Dr Mark Mobius, the peripatetic American who is the driving
force behind Templeton Emerging Markets. He is constantly on the move,
visiting and buying shares in obscure parts of the world almost before
anyone else has even realised the country has a stock market. He has been
called the Indiana Jones of the investment world, and descriptions of him
invariably include the word 'guru'. His striking appearance - small, tanned
and bald - helps make him a memorable figure. But the real test in the
investment world is the performance of your funds - and Mobius qualifies as
a force to be reckoned with on that score too.
Another home-grown personality hit the headlines last year, when his
brainchild for a time became the largest UK investment trust ever launched -
Julian Baring's Mercury World Mining trust. Baring has spent his career
analysing and investing in commodity and mining stocks, making his
reputation with his management of the Mercury Gold &amp; General unit trust.
Last year, his persuasive powers were strong enough to attract Pounds 425 to
a fund which under normal circumstances would have been lucky to go much
over Pounds 50m.
Other managers with a strong following include Anthony Bolton, who manages
Fidelity European values, and Ed Merner of Schroders, who is about to be
launched on the investment trust world with the new Schroder Japanese fund,
after making his name with unit trusts.
Like those of any other stock market sector, the ups and downs and intrigues
of the investment trust sector are monitored by analysts employed by the
large stockbroking firms. The select few who follow investment trusts at
Smith New Court, SG Warburg, NatWest and Credit Lyonnais Laing produce
regular reports and statistical analysis, intended mainly for institutional
investors, though some of their research is also available to private
investors.
SG Warburg, for example, produces an annual private investor guide with
clear explanations for the novice investor, while Credit Lyonnais Laing's
yearly manual is a very comprehensive reference work with detailed
background information on the trusts and their managers. The NatWest annual,
written by Robin Angus and Hamish Buchan, can be an entertaining read as
well as a source of useful information.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6722 Management Investment, Open-End.
    P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
</IN>
