<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / FT Guide to Investment Trusts (6): Taking a chance on the
unknown - Launches in a sector seen as the domain of institutional investors
have attracted money from ordinary savers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Specialisation has become an increasingly notable feature of the investment
trust industry.
Perhaps because there are already plenty of general funds doing a perfectly
good job, the only way that fund managers can entice investors into a new
trust is by giving some novel, possibly unique, twist to its investment
strategy.
The more cynical might describe these as gimmicks. But, to be fair, there is
often a good investment idea hidden somewhere behind the hype.
Flourishing areas recently have included Latin America and Japan, while
there have also been many single-country or narrowly-based regional funds
for previously untouched regions, including India, Israel, Taiwan and
central Europe.
Other specialisms popular at the moment are smaller companies, venture
capital and privatisations, while last year's launches included the giant
Mercury World Mining fund, as well as plenty of smaller company and emerging
markets funds.
The general rule is that the more specialist a fund is, the riskier and more
volatile it is likely to be. For example, buying shares in a single-country
fund for Indonesia would be a much bigger gamble than buying a regional Far
Eastern fund, or a global emerging markets one.
Obviously, the risk-rating of a specialist trust also depends on the
riskiness of its holdings. A venture capital fund, which invests in small
start-up companies and management buy-outs, is inherently more risky than,
say, the two European privatisation trusts, which buy shares in large
formerly state-owned companies.
As usual, the flip side to this argument is that the greater the risk, the
greater the potential reward. So the European privatisation trusts are
likely to move steadily ahead with performance comparable to general
European trusts, while a good venture capital manager in the right economic
climate could produce outstanding returns.
There is no doubt that you are more likely to find a specialist trust at the
top of the performance tables than a general one, but the specialists often
hog the bottom end of the scale as well. For example, if you had invested
Pounds 100 in the TR Property investment trust in April 1989, by April this
year your investment would have shrunk to about Pounds 76 - hardly a
sparkling performance. But if you had invested Pounds 100 in April last
year, it would have turned into about Pounds 182 a year later -
outperforming most other trusts over the same period.
Extremes like this are usually to be found only in highly specialised,
cyclical areas like smaller companies, venture capital, commodities and
single-country funds in emerging markets. Poor timing can be disastrous, but
if you judge the moment correctly, the rewards can be great.
The added risk with investment trusts launched to cash in on a fashion, as
many of them are, is that if a specialist area falls out of favour, probably
because it is underperforming, the shares of trusts in that area will become
difficult to sell. The share price may then drop to a wide discount to net
asset value, compounding the effect of poor investment returns.
Specialist trusts have traditionally been the domain of the institutional
investors, who use them as a way of sub-contracting the management of part
of their portfolios, while all but the most sophisticated private investors
have stuck to more general trusts.
However, some of the recent specialist launches have pulled in large amounts
of money from the general public. The Fleming Chinese trust, launched last
year, was extremely popular with private investors, who had been reading
about the booming Chinese economy. It was heavily over-subscribed - Pounds
15m worth of shares were available through a public offer, but applications
were received for Pounds 40m.
Some sections of the industry are, no doubt, delighted by this extra source
of demand, but it is causing concern to others, who worry that people are
buying inappropriate investments without taking advice about the
implications.
Legal restrictions mean that new issues can be advertised much more freely
than existing trusts. So new issues tend to grab all the attention, while
longstanding general trusts cannot advertise their attractions except
indirectly by promoting Peps or savings schemes.
Fund managers are always alarmed when they discover that, among their
investors, are elderly people who have put a substantial chunk of their
savings into an emerging markets trust, with all the rest in a building
society. This is not a good spread of risk. All the industry can do is
plaster health warnings across application forms, but often these seem only
to whet the appetite further.
Most financial advisers emphasise that, unless you are very sure of your
investment nose and can afford to lose the money you are investing, highly
specialised trusts should form no more than 5 or 10 per cent of your
portfolio.
But there will always be people who see investment as an entertaining and
occasionally profitable hobby, akin to doing the pools. They tend to put a
little money into whichever exotic fund is being promoted each month, and
will follow its progress with interest. The good news for that breed of
investor is that the supply of exciting new specialist funds shows no sign
of drying up in the foreseeable future.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
