<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / FT Guide to Investment Trusts (2): A foot on the other
side's turf - Scheherazade Daneshkhu examines the increased competition for
investors' money that has followed the fall in interest rates, tempting
savers out of building societies and into equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On the face of it, unit and investment trusts have more in common than
divides them.
It is in both their interests to attract investors into equities, and both
are able to argue that, as collective funds, they offer private investors a
relatively cheap route into a diversified holding.
However, behind these common goals lies the competition for investors'
money, which has accelerated as the fall in UK interest rates over the past
18 months has brought private investors out of the building societies and
into equities.
Investment trusts, with a history dating back to the 1860s, are often
regarded as the more sophisticated investor's choice; but unit trusts, which
have been around only since the 1930s, have been skilled at mass marketing
and at appealing to bank and building society customers.
They have had an advantage here over investment trusts, which have been
restricted in their advertising by the Companies Act prohibiting quoted
companies from advertising their shares. Packaged products, such as savings
schemes and personal equity plans are exempt from this restriction, and
investment trusts have concentrated their marketing on these products.
Unit trusts also pay 3 per cent commission to independent financial
advisers, giving them a distribution advantage over investment trusts.
In recent years, some fund management groups traditionally associated with
one product have ventured on to the other's turf. Before 1991, Fidelity, for
example, did not manage any investment trusts. It now has two: European
Values and Japanese Values.
Mary Blair, Fidelity's product development director, says that the company
decided three years ago that it wanted to enter the investment trust
business, to attract those institutional and retail clients who will only
buy investment trusts and not unit trusts. The ability of investment trusts
to gear by borrowing money also has investment attractions, says Ms Blair.
On the other hand, Foreign &amp; Colonial, manager of the world's oldest
investment trust, has been extraordinarily successful in raising Pounds 500m
within a year for the High Income unit trust, launched in February 1993 with
the German Hypo bank and aimed at building society customers.
F&amp;C's Craig Walton said that, although the company had had unit trusts since
1983, it had decided two years ago on a marketing drive for its unit trust
business. The main reason for launching the High Income Fund as a unit,
rather than investment, trust was that it could be sold through the IFA
network.
Structure
Although some investors may have a clear-cut understanding of which type of
trust to choose, each has its advantages and disadvantages.
From two fundamental structural differences between the trusts stem the
characteristics of each. Unit trusts are open-ended and able to create units
when there is demand, whereas an investment trust has a fixed number of
shares. While investment trusts are traded on the stock market in the same
way as other shares, unit trusts are not quoted companies.
This means that, while the value of units is fixed according to the value of
the underlying assets in a unit trust, the price of shares in an investment
trust fluctuates according to market demand. At periods when demand has been
low, investment trusts have tended to trade at a discount to their net asset
value.
In the early 1980s, discounts could be as wide as 25 to 30 per cent, but the
average discount fell to 12 per cent at the beginning of 1993 and then to 4
per cent in January this year, and has widened since. Private investor
demand, against the background of low interest rates - as well as efforts by
the industry to pull in a steady stream of new money with monthly savings
schemes introduced about a decade ago - has helped to achieve this
narrowing. Split-capital trusts, which separate the functions of capital
growth and income, have also given investment trusts an appeal to a wider
circle of investors.
The narrowing of the discount has helped to give investment trusts their
superior performance over unit trusts in the past 10 years. (See table - the
investment trust figures do not take account of charges and are therefore
comparable with those for unit trusts quoted on an offer-to-offer basis.)
But with discounts historically low, investors cannot necessarily expect the
same level of returns in the next 10 years.
Charges
Many investors are attracted to investment trusts because of their charging
structure. Unit trusts have an initial charge of 5 to 6 per cent, and the
bid/offer spread - the difference in price between buying and selling units
 -can be greater. In addition, there is an annual management charge, often
of 1.5 per cent.
Since investment trusts are bought in the market, there is no comparable
initial charge. Instead there is stockbroker's commission of 1.5 to 2 per
cent (less in savings schemes), 0.5 per cent stamp duty on the purchase of
the shares and the marketmaker's buying and selling spread. The annual fee
is lower than that of unit trusts at about 0.5 to 0.75 per cent.
Liquidity
In falling markets, unit trust managers face the problem of redemptions, and
can find themselves having to sell holdings quickly if investors want to
liquidate their units.
This is both good and bad from the investors' point of view. It means that
they can get out quickly by making a phone call; but if they want to stay in
the trust, its long-term performance can be badly hit by the fund manager
having to sell stock he would otherwise have preferred to hold. Investment
trust managers are spared this problem, but instead their investors are
likely to find the trust moving to a deep discount if it becomes unpopular.
If the investment trust is small, investors may find it difficult to sell
out because of a shortage of buyers.
James Higgins, of fee-based independent financial advisers Chamberlain de
Broe, says: 'We do tend to favour investment trusts, because of their
flexibility. They are ideal for regular savings plans, particularly because
most now have plans with very low dealing charges. However, if a
particularly attractive investment trust is standing at a premium, we might
recommend a comparable unit trust. An example is the use of City of London
Emerging Markets unit trust, instead of Templeton's investment trust.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
