<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / The Lex Column: Lasmo/Enterprise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lasmo has now been forced twice in a week to modify extravagant statements
that it has made in trying to fend off Enterprise's hostile bid. In the
latest and most serious case, the Takeover Panel said Lasmo's allegations
that Enterprise had breached accounting standards were stronger than it
considered acceptable. Whatever spin Lasmo tries to put on it, investors
will take a dim view of a management that shoots from the hip in this way.
Still, the substance of Lasmo's allegations have hit Enterprise hard.
Enterprise's decision to write down sharply the value of assets at the time
they were acquired in the late 1980s has reduced depreciation charges and
boosted reported earnings. This has reinforced the impression that
Enterprise cannot really afford to pay dividends at their current level. The
company's share price has suffered. At last night's close of 382p, its
all-paper offer was worth only 124p a share compared with Lasmo's share
price of 142p.
This 18p gap is the most important indicator of how the bid battle is
proceeding. Enterprise has sought to close it by arguing that it can add
value to Lasmo's business. But these arguments carry no more conviction than
they did at the start of the bid. That leaves Enterprise in the same bind.
It needs to improve the offer, probably by offering significant amounts of
cash, if it is to clinch Lasmo. But that would put its ability to maintain
dividends to its own shareholders under even greater pressure.
</TEXT>
