<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / N Korea faces punishment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON, MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US, South Korea and Japan are seeking ways to punish North Korea's
obduracy, after the International Atomic Energy Agency declared Pyongyang
had broken the continuity of nuclear safeguards inspections by unloading
spent nuclear fuel from a reactor without supervision.
As the 15-month dispute over North Korea's nuclear programme reached a
critical phase, President Bill Clinton said in Rome he expected to discuss
the crisis with Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
Mr Hans Blix, IAEA chief, last night briefed members of the United Nations
Security Council, which may next week consider imposing economic sanctions
against Pyongyang.
Mrs Madeleine Albright, US envoy to the UN, termed Mr Blix's report
'alarming'.
She said US, Japanese and South Korean officials, who held talks in
Washington yesterday, would hold further discussions at the weekend. The US
would then begin consultations in the Security Council on 'timing,
objectives and substance of a sanctions resolution in the near future'.
The IAEA wanted to select and analyse the spent fuel rods to see whether
North Korea had diverted plutonium from the reactor in 1989 to develop at
least one atomic bomb, as claimed by US intelligence. It said it was no
longer possible to verify independently if North Korea had diverted
plutonium.
Pyongyang has warned that sanctions will be considered 'an act of war' and
threatened to withdraw from the nuclear non-proliferation treaty (NPT),
expanding its nuclear programme. But both China and Russia, which wield veto
power in the Security Council, suggested yesterday they would not support
immediate imposition of sanctions.
Mr Tang Jiaxuan, Chinese deputy foreign minister, said on a visit to Seoul
that negotiations with North Korea must continue and sanctions 'may only
complicate matters.'
In Moscow Mr Yeltsin told visiting South Korean President Kim Young-sam that
the Security Council must issue an explicit warning to North Korea before
resorting to sanctions. But he said Russia would back sanctions if North
Korea withdrew from the NPT.
The US, Japan and South Korea are considering imposing their own economic
embargo if China blocks a sanctions resolution in the UN.
South Korea is preparing measures to wind down its trade with the North,
which amounted to Dollars 180m (Pounds 120m) last year. Japan may try to
shut off cash remittances by Korean-Japanese, Pyongyang's largest source of
hard currency. The three countries will consult on increased defence
measures in preparation for a possible conflict on the Korean peninsula.
</TEXT>
