<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 94 / Workers in public sector 'take more sick leave'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Public-sector workers take an average of 10 days sickness absence a year
compared with 7 1/2 days in the private sector, according to a survey for
the Confederation of British Industry.
Overall absence through sickness costs employers Pounds 11bn a year, says
the survey. However, it acknowledges that this could be an underestimate
because it takes no account of lost production.
If the public sector were brought into line with the private sector, says
the CBI, the saving for taxpayers could be Pounds 640m.
But the survey also shows that while the cost of absence has fallen by
Pounds 2bn, from Pounds 13bn in 1992, the number of working days lost has
increased by 5m to 166m. This reflects the growth in part-time work and the
fact that the cost of providing cover is lower for part-timers.
</TEXT>
