<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / US workers 'must share in decisions'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sustained employee participation in decision-making is a critical factor in
increasing economic performance, a panel appointed by the Clinton
administration reported yesterday.
The Commission on the Future of Worker-Management Relations, chaired by
former labour secretary John Dunlop, over the past year undertook one of the
most comprehensive examinations of US labour-management relations in 60
years.
In its 150-page report the Commission found that viable, high-quality
employee participation arrangements are rare because the structure of US
labour law, which has not changed much since the 1930s, makes managers wary
of changing traditional decision-making hierarchies.
A survey by the commission shows that 40m to 50m US workers would like to
participate in critical decisions on their job but have no opportunity to do
so.
'Employee participation has grown and is designed to increase efficiency,
performance and quality,' Mr Dunlop said. '(But) the high performance
workplace may well be limited in the eyes of employers by our existing
statutory arrangements.'
The report says only 5 per cent of employee participation programs can be
classified as 'high performance' - a full partnership between management and
labour resulting in increased productivity - even though one fifth to one
third of all employees are involved in such programmes.
The Commission has not yet published its recommendations, which could change
such fundamental aspects of US law as the National Labour Relations Act
passed under the New Deal. The Dunlop Commission's recommendations are due
out this autumn.
The Commission also found that most sectors of American society support
workers' right to unionise and participate in collective bargaining.
In practice, it discovered employees cannot always organise and elect
representatives in a manner free from coercion and interference, by either
management or union officials.
The labour secretary, Mr Robert Reich, said yesterday cases of illegal
employment practices had increased recently among a small number of US
employers.
Mr Dunlop also said his panel found that the tremendous increase in rights
and protections granted to individual workers in the last 50 years by both
state and federal legislatures has led to a flood of litigation that could
often interfere with workplace productivity.
Mr Reich said that last year 46,000 complaints of alleged labour law
violations were brought to the Department of Labour alone.
The Dunlop Commission report explains this on US reliance on the civil court
system to resolve labour disputes and rights violations, whereas other
nations use specialised, tripartite employment courts.
At time of decreasing rates of productivity growth and stagnating inflation
adjusted wages (wages for males actually fell for the first time in 75
years) the Commission hopes to be able to find common ground between
management and labour unions, Mr Dunlop said.
Mr Reich also said business and government should be alarmed by Commission
findings on the growing income gap in the US, currently the largest of any
industrialised nation. Over time, this increasing difference between rich
and poor, and educated and uneducated, would lead to a sharp erosion in both
productivity and competitiveness, he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
