FT  03 JUN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Coffee bounces back as roasters
return
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Coffee market returned to the offensive yesterday with London prices
shooting up and traders predicting more gains as supplies remain tight.
Coffee prices recovered much of Wednesday's losses with the September
futures contract at the London Commodity Exchange up Dollars 44 a tonne to
Dollars 2,080 a tonne.
Traders said that much of the speculative and hedge fund selling which had
pushed prices down on Wednesday was absent from the market and that roasters
were buying again.
'We are not seeing much new coffee come on to the market, the speculators
have taken their profits and prices look ready to move up again,' one trader
commented.
However, Mr Rubens Barbosa, Brazil's ambassador to Britain said yesterday
that producers would be damaged if prices went up much more.
The cocoa market rose higher on the coat tails of coffee with the September
futures contract increasing by Pounds 10 a tonne to Pounds 1,041 a tonne.
