<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / International Company News: Borland slumps to fourth-term
deficit as sales continue to drop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Borland International reported heavy losses for its fourth fiscal quarter
and year. The personal computer software company is restructuring its
operations and trying to stem a sharp decline in sales.
Net losses for the quarter ended March 31 were Dollars 76m, or Dollars 2.84
a share, compared with net income of Dollars 5.1m, or 19 cents, in the same
period last year.
The losses included a pre-tax restructuring charge of Dollars 14m covering
about 300 job cuts and the closure of some facilities. An additional charge
of Dollars 8.2m was recorded for the write-down of real estate assets that
the company plans to sell.
Fourth-quarter revenues were Dollars 51.0m, a 56.4 per cent decline from
Dollars 117.1m in the same period last year.
In March, 10 days before the end of the fourth quarter, Borland announced
plans to sell its spreadsheet product line, Quattro Pro, to Novell, another
software company, for Dollars 145m. The transaction is expected to be
completed this month.
Borland said lower sales were in part attributable to a significant decline
in sales of Quattro Pro following the announcement of the proposed sale. The
company also blamed its revenue drop on customers waiting to buy new
versions of some of its products that are to be introduced this summer.
Borland said it expected a further operating loss in the current quarter and
that sales would be adversely affected by the same factors, as well as by
disruptions from the restructuring of its European operations.
The company plans to take a one-time charge of about Dollars 16m for the
acquisition of Report-Smith, a software company.
Borland amended results for the third quarter ended December 31 to include a
Dollars 3.3m charge for marketing commitments that had not been accounted
for previously. The charge resulted in a net loss for the third quarter of
Dollars 2.9m, compared with net income of Dollars 419,000, as originally
reported.
For the year, it reported a net loss of Dollars 69.9m, or Dollars 2.62 a
share, compared with a net loss of Dollars 49.2m, or Dollars 1.87 for fiscal
1993. Revenues for the year were Dollars 393.5m, a 15.2 per cent decrease
from Dollars 464m.
