<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / International Company News: Kmart faces defeat over plan to
sell share stakes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kmart, the US discount store group, was last night facing an embarrassing
defeat in today's vote over its plan to sell stakes of up to 30 per cent in
its four specialty retailing subsidiaries.
A growing rebellion against the board by Kmart's institutional investors
gained another influential recruit when it was joined yesterday by the
California Public Employees' Retirement System (Calpers), the biggest US
public pension fund.
The fund said it had decided to vote against Kmart's plan because it could
dilute Calpers' holdings and 'may preclude management from considering other
better alternatives'.
Calpers said it was withholding its support for the re-election of five
directors to the board to express its dissatisfaction over the 'persistent
poor performance' of the company. 'We have serious questions about who is
minding the store for shareholders at Kmart,' it said.
Calpers is one of six institutional investors to signal dissatisfaction with
Kmart's board and management over the last few days by denouncing the
company's plans.
The others are the College Retirement Equities Fund, the biggest US
institutional investor; the State of Wisconsin Investment Board, one of the
10 largest US pension funds; the Florida State Board of Administration; the
Ohio State Teachers Retirement System; and the Amalgamated Clothing and
Textile Workers Union. They hold a small percentage of Kmart's stock -
Calpers holds 2.8m of the 455.9m issued shares - but their hostility could
swing other shareholders.
Kmart earlier this week said the rebel investors were only a tiny minority
of the company's 460 institutional investors, and it hoped for a majority of
support.
